Assignment 4: Building and Evaluating Ensemble Models

Shyni David

2/18/2019

Directions

This assignment extends the work you did as part of assignment 3 using the German Credit data set. In that assignment, you built, fine-tuned, and compared the performance of four candidate classification models: a logistic regression model, a regularized linear model using an elasticnet penalty for shrinkage, a classification tree model, and a neural net model. Your primary task in this assignment is to see if you might be able to improve on the work you have done by building and assessing the performance of different ensemble models using the three main techniques/methods for ensembling: bagging, boosting, and stacking.

germancredit$response <- as.factor(ifelse(germancredit$response == 1, "Good", "Bad"))

1. BaggingBuilding multiple models (typically of the same type) from different subsamples of the training dataset.) Using this approach you will build two ensemble models: (a) a Bagged CART tree model (method=treebag), and (b) a Random Forest model (method=rf).

set.seed(1234)
cmetric = "ROC"
btree <- train(response ~., data = germancredit.train, method = "treebag", metric=cmetric,
              trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE)
)
btree
## Bagged CART 
## 
## 750 samples
##  20 predictor
##   2 classes: 'Good', 'Bad' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 676, 675, 676, 675, 676, 674, ... 
## Resampling results:
## 
##   ROC        Sens       Spec     
##   0.7611406  0.8722787  0.4533597
probsTest <- predict(btree, type="prob", newdata=germancredit.test)
predsBtree <- probsTest[,2]  ##save for later  


##AUC onthe hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(predsBtree, germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##              [,1]
## Good vs. Bad 0.76
###build a Random Forest Model
set.seed(1234)
RFmodel <- train(response ~., data = germancredit.train,  method = "rf", metric=cmetric,
               trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE)
)
probsTest <- predict(RFmodel, type="prob", newdata=germancredit.test)
predsRF <- probsTest[,2]  ##save for later

##AUC onthe hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(predsRF, germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##                   [,1]
## Good vs. Bad 0.7688762
##compare the models on the hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(cbind(predsBtree, predsRF), germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##              predsBtree   predsRF
## Good vs. Bad       0.76 0.7688762

The Random Forest model is more efficient in predicting the success and has a high AUC emphesizing higher sensitivity.

2.BoostingBuilding a strong model by successively training models on weighted versions of the training data, where more weight is given to examples that were misclassified by earlier rounds. Using this approach, you will build two ensemble models: (a) an Adaptive Tree Boosting Model (method=adaboost), and (b) an (eXtreme) Gradient Boosted Tree model (method=xgbTree)

set.seed(1234)
adatree <- train(response ~., data = germancredit.train, method = "adaboost", metric=cmetric,
               trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE)
)
probsTest <- predict(adatree, type="prob", newdata=germancredit.test)
predsAdatree <- probsTest[,2]  ##save for later

##AUC  on the hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(predsAdatree, germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##                   [,1]
## Good vs. Bad 0.7741714
###build a Boosted Tree Model using xgbTree
set.seed(1234)
xgbmodel <- train(response ~., data = germancredit.train, method = "xgbTree", metric=cmetric,
                 trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE)
)
probsTest <- predict(xgbmodel, type="prob", newdata=germancredit.test)
predsxgb <- probsTest[,2]  ##save for later


##AUC  on the hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(predsxgb, germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##                [,1]
## Good vs. Bad 0.7936
##compare the models on the hold-out/Test partition
colAUC(cbind(predsAdatree,  predsxgb), germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##              predsAdatree predsxgb
## Good vs. Bad    0.7741714   0.7936

Gradient boot model seems to better than the ADAboost model as it has higher AUC.

3. StackingCombining the predictions of multiple models via a meta-classifier (or meta-regressor for regression problems). The result is a two-tiered ensemble. The base level models are trained based on a complete training set, then the meta-model is trained on the outputs of the base level model as features. You can manually build a stacked ensemble model, but the CaretEnsemble package makes this task much simpler. Use the caretList function in CaretEnsemble (Links to an external site.)Links to an external site. package to rebuild and tune the four base-level models you built in assignment #3, and then using caretStack build a glm as the meta-model to aggregate the predictions of the four base-level models.

set.seed(1234)

library(caretEnsemble)
## 
## Attaching package: 'caretEnsemble'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     autoplot
my_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", # for cross-validation
                           number = 10, # number of k-folds
                           savePredictions = "final",
                           summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs = TRUE,
                           allowParallel = TRUE)

#train a list of models all at the same time REPEATS WHAT WE HAVE DONE BEFORE,
model_list <- caretList(response ~., data = germancredit.train,
                        trControl = my_control,
                        methodList = c("glm", "rpart", "nnet"),
                        metric="ROC",
                        tuneList = NULL,   
                        continue_on_fail = FALSE, 
                        preProcess = c("center", "scale"))

set.seed(1234)
#create an ensemble that is a linear combination of model_list
ensemble_1 <- caretEnsemble(model_list, 
                            metric = "ROC", 
                            trControl = my_control)

#################################Stacking######################################################

###called BLENDING
#CaretStack
set.seed(1234)

# Ensemble the predictions of `models` to form a new combined prediction based on glm
# The stacking algorithm simply builds a second caret model on top of the existing models 
# (using their predictions as input)
ensemble_2 <- caretStack(model_list, 
                         method = "glm",
                         metric = "ROC", 
                         trControl = my_control)

print(ensemble_2)
## A glm ensemble of 2 base models: glm, rpart, nnet
## 
## Ensemble results:
## Generalized Linear Model 
## 
## 750 samples
##   3 predictor
##   2 classes: 'Good', 'Bad' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 676, 675, 676, 675, 676, 674, ... 
## Resampling results:
## 
##   ROC        Sens       Spec     
##   0.7752458  0.8875544  0.4351779
model_preds2 <- model_preds
model_preds2$ensemble2 <- predict(ensemble_2, type="prob", newdata=germancredit.test)
 
colAUC(model_preds2, germancredit.test$response, plotROC=TRUE)

##                    glm     rpart      nnet ensemble1 ensemble2
## Good vs. Bad 0.7798857 0.7317714 0.7670857 0.7916952 0.7916952
#lets try to stack random forest

                         method = "rf",
                         metric = "ROC", 
                      trControl = my_control)

Ensemble2 model created by stacking seems to have the highest accuracy in prediction with the highest AUC that corresponds to a prpbability that a positive case will have a higher score than the negative case.
